# Architecture And Code Organization

- Follow the active scaffold only; do not add app features, infrastructure, or abstractions before the scaffold asks for them.
- Keep files small and focused. If a file starts mixing unrelated responsibilities, extract a service, hook, helper, DTO, or component that matches the existing folder style.
- Separate UI rendering from business logic, network calls, persistence, validation, and data shaping.
- Prefer readable composition over large all-in-one modules. Screens/controllers should orchestrate; services/helpers should own logic.
- Keep shared behavior in a single place when it is reused by more than one feature. Avoid premature shared abstractions for one-off scaffold code.
- Add tests near the behavior being introduced, scaled to the scaffold risk and done criteria.
